    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1891-07-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1891-07-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="156"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d156">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Egan</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Blaine</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1891-07-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 28, 1891</hi>.</date> (Received September
                        26.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 183.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to my telegram of March
                    8, and my dispatch No. 148, of April 1 last, conveying the request of the
                    Chilean Government that the United States would permit one of its war ships to
                    convey from Valparaiso to Montevideo a quantity of bar silver which it desired
                    to export for the purpose of paying the interest on the national debt abroad, to
                    which communication I did not receive any reply. I now beg to state that the
                    English Government has placed the British war ship <hi rend="italic"
                        >Espiègle</hi> at the service of the Government of Chile to convey this bar
                    silver to England and that she is now taking it on board at Talcahuano.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Patrick Egan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
